00:31:49.590 --> 00:31:50.590
Bob Landay: Mmm hmm.

00:31:50.590 --> 00:31:51.590
&gt;&gt;Female Speaker 4: [unintelligible]

00:31:51.590 --> 00:31:54.320
&gt;&gt;Bob Landay: Do you? [Bob laughs] I never
look at that.

00:31:54.320 --> 00:31:57.190
&gt;&gt;Female #4: We have seen maybe two of the
children the kids went to high school with

00:31:57.190 --> 00:32:01.340
turn up in a domestic situation at
home where it turned into a domestic violence

00:32:01.340 --> 00:32:07.831
situation and somebody was frightened enough
to call the cops--

00:32:07.831 --> 00:32:08.831
&gt;&gt;Bob Landay: Mmm hmm.

00:32:08.831 --> 00:32:11.529
&gt;&gt;Female #4:--and then the whole town sees
it. And we knew them; they were all good people,

00:32:11.529 --> 00:32:12.529
and--

00:32:12.529 --> 00:32:13.840
&gt;&gt;Bob Landay: Right, right.

00:32:13.840 --> 00:32:19.990
&gt;&gt;Female #4: --seemingly to be happy people
and took good care of--

00:32:19.990 --> 00:32:22.320
&gt;&gt;Bob Landay: And still may be good people--

00:32:22.320 --> 00:32:23.320
&gt;&gt;Female #4: Oh, yeah.

00:32:23.320 --> 00:32:27.970
&gt;&gt;Bob Landay: I mean, good people do bad things;
bad people do good things; good families produce

00:32:27.970 --> 00:32:34.970
bad kids; bad families produce
good kids and it's just a complicated thing.

00:32:34.970 --> 00:32:43.659
And that's why it's hard in thrillers, in
the ordinary run of the mill because the temptation

00:32:43.659 --> 00:32:50.289
is to flatten these characters. And if
you make your villain into a monster, then

00:32:50.289 --> 00:32:57.350
it becomes very easy to plot because it's
very easy to go after a monster. But I didn't

00:32:57.350 --> 00:33:02.809
want that; I didn't want Jacob to be a monster.
I didn't want this to be The Bad Seed, or

00:33:02.809 --> 00:33:06.679
The Omen, you know, where Damien has the
beady black eyes and you know, the minute

00:33:06.679 --> 00:33:13.139
you look at those beady black eyes, that this
is the monster.

00:33:13.139 --> 00:33:21.059
So you know, we do know these people and it's
interesting when--. I was talking with a defense

00:33:21.059 --> 00:33:26.789
lawyer the other day because when
you're a prosecutor, it’s--. You know you

00:33:26.789 --> 00:33:29.499
have all this expertise, but your expertise
is only in criminal law.

00:33:29.499 --> 00:33:30.499
[audience chuckles]

00:33:30.499 --> 00:33:35.009
So if you're going to leave the office and
not be a career prosecutor, the only place

00:33:35.009 --> 00:33:42.049
you can go is to criminal defense. A lot of
D. D.A.s get into it because you want to wear

00:33:42.049 --> 00:33:47.730
the white hat and you, at least, feel like
that is what you are doing. And to some extent

00:33:47.730 --> 00:33:54.049
you are. But you quickly realize that it becomes
more complicated than that. And so I was talking

00:33:54.049 --> 00:33:58.700
to this defense lawyer and we were
talking about just this: "Do you feel, when

00:33:58.700 --> 00:34:02.940
you defend somebody--. Say you defended a
rapist and he gets out and he

00:34:02.940 --> 00:34:09.730
re-offends." Serial rapists are run of the
mill, you know. And I asked him, “Would

00:34:09.730 --> 00:34:15.620
you feel any culpability, would you feel any
guilt?" And he said, "No, not at all." And

00:34:15.620 --> 00:34:20.420
he said, "When you get to know these people,
you start seeing them as people and you

00:34:20.420 --> 00:34:26.040
don't say 'Well, he's a rapist,'--you say,
'He's Joe and he comes from this or that background

00:34:26.040 --> 00:34:29.669
and he has this or that
psychological difficulty' and that makes it

00:34:29.669 --> 00:34:35.000
very easy to defend him." And from the prosecution
side, you're always on the other side of the

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:41.160
courtroom and you never get that opportunity
to humanize these people.

00:34:41.160 --> 00:34:48.790
So it's a difficult thing and again back to
this question, what makes people do what they

00:34:48.790 --> 00:34:56.620
do? What makes us what we are? What makes
us? What is this experience of being us?

00:34:56.620 --> 00:35:02.660
And we've all ourselves done things that we're
not proud of. We all have our little secrets,

00:35:02.660 --> 00:35:10.350
our secret shames. To begin to
understand yourself is to accept that there

00:35:10.350 --> 00:35:16.730
are these parts of you that are--. I don't
know if I'd say beyond your control but very

00:35:16.730 --> 00:35:23.540
very complicated and where your motivations,
well, can't even be called motivations properly.

00:35:23.540 --> 00:35:29.430
You might be what you are and there's
only so much you can decide to do or not do.

00:35:29.430 --> 00:35:32.910
It's a scary thought.

00:35:32.910 --> 00:35:34.470
Yeah?

00:35:34.470 --> 00:35:44.670
&gt;&gt;Female #5: Having done this, as a writer,
what unfinished business do you have for the

00:35:44.670 --> 00:35:45.670
next book?

00:35:45.670 --> 00:35:46.670
[Bob laughs]

00:35:46.670 --> 00:35:48.780
&gt;&gt;Bob Landay: This is it, I've answered my
questions. I can just kick back and retire

00:35:48.780 --> 00:35:49.780
now.

00:35:49.780 --> 00:35:51.150
&gt;&gt;Female #5: This would be great. If it works--

00:35:51.150 --> 00:35:58.610
&gt;&gt;Bob Landay: It would be great. You know
it's funny, I don't--. First of all when I

00:35:58.610 --> 00:36:03.890
was writing this, I never had this sense that
this is the book, this is the big break out.

00:36:03.890 --> 00:36:11.950
This is the sum of all my business as a writer.
I just thought it was the third book.

00:36:11.950 --> 00:36:16.640
I thought it was incrementally better; maybe
incrementally more interesting. Or at least

00:36:16.640 --> 00:36:22.870
aimed at a broader market then what came before.
But then I hope that I should always be improving;

00:36:22.870 --> 00:36:27.040
that I should always be getting incrementally
better. So when this book

00:36:27.040 --> 00:36:35.230
exploded, it came as a surprise to me and
I still think of it as having nothing to with,

00:36:35.230 --> 00:36:42.290
– your job, your growth as a artist. I don't
mean to be too highfalutin' about this, but

00:36:42.290 --> 00:36:48.000
you're always improving along a much longer
arc in trying to get better and better and

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:52.840
that's some books sell a lot and some sell
a little. Has nothing to do with that steady

00:36:52.840 --> 00:36:57.820
arc of improvement. So I kind of feel that
this is one data point here and that's here;

00:36:57.820 --> 00:37:02.070
the sales might be up here, but the book is
where it is and, you know, I hope to keep

00:37:02.070 --> 00:37:07.160
going.

00:37:07.160 --> 00:37:12.260
The next book gets, and I hesitate to talk
about the next book because everything always

00:37:12.260 --> 00:37:17.650
changes so what I tell you now, by the time
I get back to my car, could be out of date.

00:37:17.650 --> 00:37:18.650
[laughter]

00:37:18.650 --> 00:37:28.930
So, it's about this question of evil. What
makes people to do--? What enables people

00:37:28.930 --> 00:37:37.270
to do the things that they do? We talk about
evil as if it's this free floating force.

00:37:37.270 --> 00:37:42.890
We talk about it as a noun when it's really
an adjective. It's part of all of our

00:37:42.890 --> 00:37:51.610
capability and that's kind of what I wanted
to continue exploring. This sort of, the idea

00:37:51.610 --> 00:37:57.410
of Jacob Barber as sort one embodiment
of what our capabilities are is interesting,

00:37:57.410 --> 00:38:02.370
and it's interesting because of his background
and his particular characteristics, but

00:38:02.370 --> 00:38:10.710
the idea that this is some shadowy unknowable
boy with all of these influences, physical

00:38:10.710 --> 00:38:16.770
and social, that drive him to be the things
that they are, removes him in a way from the

00:38:16.770 --> 00:38:25.340
ordinary. And I want to, I wonder what would
happen if the ordinary, if the Barber

00:38:25.340 --> 00:38:31.540
really brushed up against someone who was
evil and who truly was capable of this and

00:38:31.540 --> 00:38:34.580
what would that mean? And what would they,
as

00:38:34.580 --> 00:38:38.320
lawyers, as in Andy Barber, how would they
react to that?

00:38:38.320 --> 00:38:42.030
And that's kind of the idea. I can't really
get into specifics, not because I'm being

00:38:42.030 --> 00:38:45.410
cagey, but because I really don't know them.
[laughter]

00:38:45.410 --> 00:38:51.671
And this is the great frustration of this
year is that it's been--. As much as a fun

00:38:51.671 --> 00:38:58.850
ride that it's been being out there with
Defending Jacob, it's distracting. And it's

00:38:58.850 --> 00:39:05.440
distracting out of proportion to the actual
time doing it. I was having this discussion

00:39:05.440 --> 00:39:13.280
with another writer the other day about why
this throws your writing so off the rails.

00:39:13.280 --> 00:39:18.590
And the common question that I get is, "Now
do you feel all this pressure to write a book

00:39:18.590 --> 00:39:25.030
that's another hit?" And I kind of don't because
I feel like I'm my own harshest

00:39:25.030 --> 00:39:31.951
critic by far and so the idea that somebody's
going to say mean things about my book, is

00:39:31.951 --> 00:39:38.010
I promise you, they could not say meaner
things than I say to myself.

00:39:38.010 --> 00:39:46.240
So you do want to improve though and that's
kind of where it's at. But it's been hard

00:39:46.240 --> 00:39:50.600
having the book take off because when you
come to events like this, I stand in front

00:39:50.600 --> 00:39:58.040
of you now and I'm the public face of an author
and you know you all look at me in a

00:39:58.040 --> 00:40:04.390
certain way as the guy who has written this
book. And I have these pat answers, practiced

00:40:04.390 --> 00:40:11.280
answers because I've had these conversations
before and so it's very--. It's one thing

00:40:11.280 --> 00:40:18.480
to stand up here to be this, the public thing,
that an author is, but eventually you go back

00:40:18.480 --> 00:40:22.530
to
your desk and the way I heard it described

00:40:22.530 --> 00:40:30.430
by this other author was, "You're never quite
as alone at your desk as you were before."

00:40:30.430 --> 00:40:38.480
That's because this public thing that I have
to be when I'm out publicizing the book is

00:40:38.480 --> 00:40:42.960
the opposite of what you're trying to be
when you're at your desk. And you’re just

00:40:42.960 --> 00:40:51.540
trying to channel these other people and trying
to be this, as open and as transparent as

00:40:51.540 --> 00:40:59.750
you can be. You're trying to disappear and
that's hard to get back to. And the more you

00:40:59.750 --> 00:41:06.120
do this, the more you stand up here
like the author, capitol "A", it becomes very

00:41:06.120 --> 00:41:15.410
hard to be that mass of insecurities and sensitivity
that you need to be in order to do

00:41:15.410 --> 00:41:22.350
this. Or at least for me. I've always wondered
about these public sort of celebrity authors,

00:41:22.350 --> 00:41:28.350
you know, the Norman Mailer types,
who can be this celebrity author and then

00:41:28.350 --> 00:41:35.010
immediately go to their desk and just become
the novelist again. I don't seem that

00:41:35.010 --> 00:41:42.710
ability to throw the switch and yet I can't
go back to sort of being the guy who lived

00:41:42.710 --> 00:41:46.510
in his mother's basement and was writing
books that nobody read, you know?

00:41:46.510 --> 00:41:50.450
So not that it was so great to live in your
mom's basement--

00:41:50.450 --> 00:41:51.450
[laughter]

00:41:51.450 --> 00:41:55.820
But it's complicated. It's complicated. I
certainly haven't got it figured out.

00:41:55.820 --> 00:42:00.120
&gt;&gt;Male #2: Did you actually live in your mom's
basement?

00:42:00.120 --> 00:42:01.120
[Bob laughs]

00:42:01.120 --> 00:42:06.270
&gt;&gt;Bob Landay: Not only did I live in my mom's
basement, when I got serious about this, I

00:42:06.270 --> 00:42:08.430
used to--. I was at the D.A.'s office and
I

00:42:08.430 --> 00:42:11.970
was working, working. I was doing it nights
and weekends and that's really hard to do,

00:42:11.970 --> 00:42:15.660
especially with that job because it's not
like--. That's not a clock punching kind of

00:42:15.660 --> 00:42:20.150
job, I mean, you're in or you're out. So eventually
what I would do is I would take a

00:42:20.150 --> 00:42:24.560
leave from there and I would pull up my retirement
money and I would live on that. And I would

00:42:24.560 --> 00:42:27.890
work and work and work until the
book either died, or the money ran out and

00:42:27.890 --> 00:42:30.360
then I'd go back and I'd start trying cases
again.

00:42:30.360 --> 00:42:35.050
And then as I got more serious about it, I
left there. I bartended over at Flat Top Johnny's

00:42:35.050 --> 00:42:40.380
across the way. And that is what I would do
at night, and I would write during the day.

00:42:40.380 --> 00:42:43.840
You should all go to Flat Top Johnny's by
the way. Have you all been? Great place,

00:42:43.840 --> 00:42:51.160
that's the end of my plug for Flat Top Johnny's
but I do love it there. And when that wasn't

00:42:51.160 --> 00:42:59.110
enough, yeah, I--. And this was at age
thirty-six, seven, eight, you know, I'm a

00:42:59.110 --> 00:43:05.020
grown man moving into my mom's basement. It's
not good. When I got married, when I met

00:43:05.020 --> 00:43:08.760
the woman who is now my wife, the mother of
my children, I was this thirty-something year

00:43:08.760 --> 00:43:10.470
old guy living in his mom's basement.

00:43:10.470 --> 00:43:17.650
It's even worse, I would go to cut out distractions,
she had this walk-in clos--like sweater closet,

00:43:17.650 --> 00:43:20.780
and I would run an extension
cord from the nearest outlet and I would sit

00:43:20.780 --> 00:43:26.300
in this closet typing on my laptop. And so
I was this shut in, you know? [chuckles]

00:43:26.300 --> 00:43:31.460
That's kind of what I was doing, and I was
churning out manuscript after manuscript and,

00:43:31.460 --> 00:43:37.990
yeah, so you know the idea that you from
that, from your mom's sweater closet with

00:43:37.990 --> 00:43:47.980
an extension cord under the door to this,
is phenomenal. Though it seems to have happened

00:43:47.980 --> 00:43:54.630
very fast, and yet, when I look at the arc
of it, I go back long before that first published

00:43:54.630 --> 00:44:01.400
book and I go back to ten years before to
this weird guy in his mom's basement. So for

00:44:01.400 --> 00:44:02.930
me, it's all part of a much longer story.

00:44:02.930 --> 00:44:03.930
Yeah?

00:44:03.930 --> 00:44:09.650
&gt;&gt;Female #6: I know you talk with other writers.
Can you talk a little bit about writer's groups

00:44:09.650 --> 00:44:11.950
or whatever, did they--

00:44:11.950 --> 00:44:16.490
&gt;&gt;Bob Landay: I don't know about writer groups,
honestly. I've never been in a writer's group.

00:44:16.490 --> 00:44:24.380
I've never taken a class, any of that stuff.
Which may be why it's taken me so long to

00:44:24.380 --> 00:44:27.300
get this together. [laughs softly]

00:44:27.300 --> 00:44:36.210
So the writers that I meet, I meet through
events. Book events, conventions, publicity

00:44:36.210 --> 00:44:42.870
things, book store readings, whatever it is.
And I'm always really excited to meet them.

00:44:42.870 --> 00:44:48.440
I feel like--. Writers are like cats, you
know, they're not truly social animals. So

00:44:48.440 --> 00:44:55.200
we're off doing this job which requires complete
solitude and yet when you come together and

00:44:55.200 --> 00:45:01.910
you realize, "Oh my God, there's someone else
out there, in his mom's sweater closet writing--".

00:45:01.910 --> 00:45:13.510
That is a huge comfort. So I'm always excited
to meet other authors and it's a great thing

00:45:13.510 --> 00:45:18.820
to realize there are other people who feel
as you do. There is a whole writer's scene

00:45:18.820 --> 00:45:25.820
out there and I'm just not part of it and
I--. It's not that I choose to be or choose

00:45:25.820 --> 00:45:33.570
not to be, it's just not my personality so
–. I'm kind of a secretive, shy person.

00:45:33.570 --> 00:45:34.570
So--

00:45:34.570 --> 00:45:43.870
That's it. Alright. Thank you all for coming
and it's been fun. All right.

00:45:43.870 --> 00:45:44.480
[Applause]

